        <h3>A major event, shaped by more than biology</h3>
        <p>Apart from carrying out basic functions such as breathing, eating, and sleeping, all organisms fulfil the duty of reproduction. While other animals carry out this at free will, reproduction in humans is associated with profound psychological effects and social impact, and is also influenced by non-biological factors like environment, society, education, and economic status. Women in reproductive age should be aware of facts related to pregnancy, the labour process, neonatal care, and puerperium — the return of pre-pregnancy physiological status.</p>

        <h3>The three trimesters</h3>
        <p>Child bearing is a major event in a woman's life, and the period of gestation is divided into three trimesters: the first from week 1 to week 12 after conception, the second from week 13 through 28, and the third from week 29 through 40. During this period, the mother's metabolism increases in response to fetal and placental growth, usually causing a 10&ndash;14 kg increase in body weight. Monitoring maternal weight gain or loss gives valuable information about fetal wellbeing and should be checked routinely. Calcium, protein, iron, and other nutrient supplementation is needed to meet the demands of the rapidly growing fetus.</p>

        <p>Some conditions are secondary to the pregnancy itself, while others simply occur during pregnancy — it is useful to be aware of the difference between "disorders caused by pregnancy" and "diseases that can occur during pregnancy".</p>

        <h3>Disorders caused by pregnancy</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Hyperemesis gravidarum</li>
          <li>Hypertensive disorders</li>
          <li>Rhesus (Rh) incompatibility</li>
          <li>Genital tract bleeding in late pregnancy</li>
          <li>Placenta praevia</li>
          <li>Polyhydramnios and oligohydramnios</li>
          <li>Obstetric cholestasis</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Diseases that can occur during pregnancy</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Asymptomatic or symptomatic urinary tract infection</li>
          <li>Acute renal failure and chronic renal diseases</li>
          <li>Anemia — iron/folic acid deficiency, hemorrhagic, or hemolytic</li>
          <li>Hyperthyroidism and hypothyroidism</li>
          <li>Prolactinemia and hypopituitarism</li>
          <li>Gestational diabetes</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Bleeding during pregnancy: the terminology</h3>
        <p>Bleeding from the genital tract is named differently based on its nature and timing. It is called antepartum hemorrhage when occurring after week 24 of pregnancy but before labour — often due to miscarriage or a threatened abortion, which can have both maternal and fetal causes. Bleeding in excess of 500 ml following labour, or within 24 hours after childbirth, is primary partum hemorrhage; bleeding after that 24-hour window is secondary partum hemorrhage. Delivery before 37 weeks is preterm labour, and malposition or malpresentation of the fetus may necessitate a caesarian delivery.</p>

        <h3>Puerperium: returning to your pre-pregnancy state</h3>
        <p>Pregnancy is associated with many physiological alterations and potential pathologies. Puerperium — the return to pre-pregnant status — varies by organ system, ranging from a few hours to several weeks after delivery. Women may feel weepy and depressed after delivery, and puerperium can be affected by factors like partum pyrexia, anemia, and inadequate sleep.</p>

        <h3>Caring for a newborn</h3>
        <p>A newborn needs close monitoring — simple parameters like breathing rate, breathing pattern, cry, and skin pallor can reveal something going wrong early. Breastfeeding is an important step, promoting mother&ndash;infant bonding while imparting immunity to the baby. Neonatal jaundice can happen in some babies and needs prompt intervention. A breastfeeding mother should also plan contraception — with several methods available, the choice should be decided with a doctor's advice.</p>

        <h3>About the BMD Calculator method</h3>
        <p>The recent interim report from the WHO task force for osteoporosis recommends determining BMD via a DXA scan for diagnosing fracture and osteoporosis-related fracture risks — the current gold standard, since other methods carry radiation hazards or inaccuracy. In an alternative approach, e-healthwatch's BMD Calculator uses anthropometric factors (age, height, weight) together with geometric factors from the upper femoral region measured on a digital X-ray: hip axis length (HAL), neck shaft angle (NSA), and neck width (NW). HAL is the distance from the centre of the femoral head to the base of the greater trochanter; NSA is the angle between the axis of the head/neck and the shaft of the femur.</p>

